{
  "doc_id": "19766",
  "text": "To get insights into the mechanisms by which overexpression of SNAP-25 confers GABAergic neurons with BoNT/A sensitivity [CITATION_1] , hippocampal cultures were transfected with plasmids encoding portions of SNAP-25 (SNAP-25 and SNAP-25 ) fused to a HA-tag. SV fusion was monitored in transfected GABAergic terminals upon BoNT/A intoxication. While no significant reduction of SV exocytosis was detected at intoxicated GAD positive synapses expressing the SNAP-25 1-180 fragment, SV fusion was strongly impaired at GAD positive synapses expressing SNAP-25 (Fig. 2A-C) . SV recycling was only analyzed at terminals where the expression levels of the transfected fragment were increased of about 2-folds, excluding those terminals expressing higher protein amounts (3-8-folds, Fig. 2C ). This effect was not due to an inhibitory action of SNAP-25 fragment on SV fusion, since exogenous expression of the fragment in inhibitory neurons did not impair vesicle recycling (Fig. 2D) . These results indicate that SNAP-25 , but not SNAP-25 1-180 is able to enhance GABAergic neuron sensitivity to BoNT/A, similarly to full length SNAP-25 [CITATION_2] . It has been previously shown that BoNT/A-inhibition of SV fusion can be overcome by high calcium concentrations [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] . Based on this finding, Delgado-Martínez et al. [CITATION_6] suggested that the lower efficacy of BoNT/A in inhibiting GABAergic vesicle cycling might be attributable to the higher calcium responsiveness of GABAergic relative to glutamatergic neurons. Given SNAP-25 but not SNAP-25 negatively modulates evoked calcium responses [CITATION_7] , the possibility opens that SNAP-25 , as the full length protein, enhances BoNT/A sensitivity by reducing calcium currents. To directly address this hypothesis, cultures were treated with the membrane permeable calcium chelator BAPTA/AM (25 M) for 15 or 20 min. BAPTA/AM incubation for 15 min reduced by about 30% peak calcium transients evoked by 55 mM KCl (Fig. 3A and B) and only mildly affected depolarization-induced SV fusion at GABAergic synapses ( Fig. 3C and D) . Of note, BAPTA/AM largely increased the sensitivity of GABAergic terminals to BoNT/A (Fig. 3E  and F) . Although monitoring of Ca 2+ elevation was carried out in neuronal cell bodies, these data suggest that the higher [Ca 2+ ] i responses at GABAergic terminals can overcome the blocking action of the toxin.",
